{{Designation list | designation1 = Ramsar | designation1_date = 30 April 1997 | designation1_number = 900<ref>{{Cite web|title=Gemenc|website=[[Ramsar Convention|Ramsar]] Sites Information Service|url=https://rsis.ramsar.org/ris/900|accessdate=25 April 2018}}</ref>}}
'''Gemenc''' is a unique forest that is found between [[Szekszárd]] and [[Baja, Hungary|Baja]], in [[Hungary]]. This is the only remaining [[tidal area]] of the [[Danube]] in [[Hungary]]. The wood's fauna include [[stag]]s, [[boar]]s, [[stork]]s, [[grey heron]]s, [[gyrfalcon]]s, [[white-tailed eagle]]s, and [[kite (bird)|kite]]s. Various amphibians and reptiles can also be found. The stag population has worldwide fame, since its genetic stock is outstanding, and the stags' antlers are impressive. Due to the various watery habitats, many fish species are present.
Close to the waters, [[willow]] and [[Populus|poplar]] forests are typical. It is the habitat of the curiosity [[Freyer's purple emperor]] ({{lang-hu|Magyar színjátszólepke}}). Furthermore, Gemenc is home to 13 other sheltered butterfly species.
Farther from the rivers, large [[oak]]-[[ash tree|ash]]-[[elm]] forests spread. These are the homes of the [[stag beetle]]s, great pricorn beetles, as well as of a kind of [[spider]] which only lives in Gemenc.
Gemenc is part of the [[Danube-Drava National Park]], and it is a nature reserve.
[[Image:Gemenc2.jpg|250px|thumb|A nest in Gemenc]] {| class="wikitable" !Property!!Value |- |National park||Danube-Drava National Park |- |Country||[[Hungary]] |- |Establishment||1977 |- |Territory||340&nbsp;km²; 177.79&nbsp;km² protected |- |% of stoutly<!--not English--> protected||15.02% |- |Dimensions||In a 5–10&nbsp;km wide band along the [[Danube]] in southern Hungary |- |}
