== Special-Use Domains == ICANN/IANA has created some Special-Use domain names which are meant for special technical purposes. ICANN/IANA owns all of the Special-Use domain names.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iana.org/assignments/special-use-domain-names/special-use-domain-names.xhtml |title=Special-Use Domain Names |publisher=Iana.org |date= |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>
{|class="wikitable sortable" |- style="background:#a0d0ff;" ![[generic top-level domain|Name]] !Entity !class="unsortable"|Notes ![[Internationalized Domain Names|IDN]] ![[Domain Name System Security Extensions|DNSSEC]] |- valign="top" | [[.example]] || || Not installed as a domain name, but usable in text as an example.<br/>example.com, example.net and example.org are also reserved for this purpose but are active sites. | {{unknown}} || |- valign="top" | [[.invalid]] || || Not installed as a domain name, but usable in testing as a domain which wouldn't work. || {{unknown}} || |- valign="top" | [[.local]] || || Local network || {{unknown}} || |- valign="top" | [[.localhost]] || || Points back to own computer || {{unknown}} || |- valign="top" | [[.onion]] || || Connection to the [[Tor network]] || {{unknown}} || |- valign="top" | [[.test]] || || Meant for testing [[DNS]] software || {{unknown}} || |}
